Anonymous Fri 04 Dec 2020 14:34:14 No.34532151 Report

>>34530924
>I don't know why I have such a thing for humans being the enigmatic precursor race but I just can't help but find stuff like that incredibly interesting.
I haven't checked on the website in years, but there was a funny little project called the Orion's Arm. It's like a kind of literary think-tank aimed at creating "plausible" sci-fi setting, that would still have epic sci-fi elements. FTL travel is there, but it's super difficult to mess with physics in that way. They use crazy powerful AI that overshadow their human counterpart. Terraforming is a thing, but it takes forever. Basically the setting ignores writing convention in favor of "OK but what is actually likely to happen?" instead of "Doesn't matter if it makes sense, I want this story for thematic reasons".

For example, another interesting quirk of the setting is dealing with the Fermi Paradox. Where are all the aliens? Oh there are none. Humans are the first intelligent species to emerge in our entire galaxy. So if we're going to fill the galaxy with interesting aliens, then by god we're the ones who will have to do it. So they create tons of genetically engineered species. Some weird ones that can live in zero gravity, some that are basically just anthro kangaroos. And lots and lots of robots.
